default&#xa0;
defaultThe BBC Management’s decision to make these changes 
default- and 
defaultthe BBC Trust’s decision to wave them thr
defaultough - has
default, in each case, served to reduce the choice of listening available to audiences.
default&#xa0;
defaultThe BBC Trust’s Service 
defaultReview of
default BBC Radio 3, published in February
default 2011, admits that:
default&#xa0;
default“default…over recent years, BBC management has made changes to Radio 3 in order to make the station more accessible and welcoming to potential listeners, particularly in peak-time slots (breakfast a
defaultnd drive) as these are the key entry points for potential listeners.
default”default 
default&#xa0;
defaultHowever, we would argue that BBC Radio 3’s management is plotting a course
default firmly towards the increasing
default popularisation of the service and a dilution of its core public service output.
default Crucially, these changes erode the choice available to listeners.  This view was echoed in submissions to the BBC Trust’s Service Review consultation by the Friends of Radio 3, 
defaultby 
defaultthe Voice of the Listener and Viewer, and 
defaultby 
defaultthe Incorporated Society of Mu
defaultsicians. 
default&#xa0;
defaultThe BBC Trust acknowledged that:
default&#xa0;
default“defaultBBC management…has changed the nature of the programmes during these hours.
default”default&#xa0;
defaultAlthough, the BBC Trust then goes on to describe this as:
default&#xa0;
default              
default“defaultLegitimate.
default”default&#xa0;
defaultWe 
defaultdisagree. T
defaulthe cumulative effect of the 
defaultalterations 
defaultmade to BBC Radio 3’s output, 
defaultwhen taken collectively
default, constitute a significant change to the service
default.
default 
defaultUnder its own rules, the BBC Trust should have undertaken a Public Value Test, includ
defaulting a market impact assessment before allowing BBC Management to und
defaultertake such a radical overhaul of one of its national networks. 
default&#xa0;
defaultIt is clear from the responses to BBC Radio 3’s programming outlined above 
default(and there are many, many more similar – and some rather more trenchant – views in chatrooms online) that the liste
defaultning public, critics and
default commentators have
default taken a very differen
defaultt view of these changes than that put forward by
default 
defaultthe 
defaultBBC Trust.  
default&#xa0;
defaultRather than pushing for BBC Radio 3 to maintain its distinctiveness, the BBC Trust’s Service Review instead appears to have a
defaultctively encouraged Radio 3 to become 
defaultmore defaultlike Classic FM. 
defaultIn
default a market of 
defaultjust 
defaulttwo 
defaultclassical music radio stations in the UK, the BBC has significantly changed the output on Radio 3 in pursuit of audiences, rather than with the aim of offering distinctive and original programming content. This lessening of distinctiveness is particula
defaultrly stark in the key morning dayparts, when listening to classical music on the radio reaches the largest number of people. 
default&#xa0;
defaultBack in 1992, 
defaultClassic FM introduced a new way of broadcasting classical music on UK radio. It complemented the style and content o
defaultf BBC Radio 3’s output at the time, providing a real point of difference. Given Classic FM’s success in building audiences for classical music radio, 
defaulttwenty years later, 
defaultthe BBC now appears to have decided to ape its commercial co
defaultmpetitor, abandoning much 
defaultof the
default distinctiveness in peak
default-
defaulttime
default 
defaulthours in the process. 
default&#xa0;
defaultNo doubt, BBC Management will point to BBC Radio 3’s commitment to specialist off-peak programming, but 
defaultby so starkly changing
default 
defaultBBC Radio 3’s programming to that of
default a ‘ratings by day, reputation by
default night’ strategy in a market place
default of 
defaultjust 
defaulttwo, repres
defaulte
defaultn
defaultts a potentially serious threat to the ability of Classic FM to operate 
defaultas an 
defaulteffective commercial competitor. Classic FM is virtually unique in the classical music world in never having received a pe
defaultnny of public subsidy to fund its work; it also does not enjoy the certainty of a fixed income from the Licence Fee. 
default  
default&#xa0;
defaultNot only did the BBC Trust fail to implement a Public Value Test
default into the BBC Management’s changes to Radio 3’s output
default, but it also fai
defaultled to abide by its own ‘Competitive Impact Policy’, which requires the BBC ‘to minimise its negative competitive impacts on the wider market’.
default&#xa0;
defaultThe BBC Trust is obliged under the terms of the BBC Agreement with DCMS to undertake a Public Value Test before
default a decision is taken to make a significant ch
defaultange to a BBC service. Although this is a decision for the Trust, the BBC Agreement requires the Trust before exercising its judgement to ‘investigate or otherwise inform itself of any facts or considerations wh
defaultich it considers potentially relevant’.
default&#xa0;
defaultIt appears that no such investigation took place. 
defaultRadioCentre 
defaultrequested further detail 
defaultfrom the BBC 
defaulton the proposed strategy to make Radio 3 more accessible and welcoming under the Freedom of Information Act 2000 
default(Letter, 24
defaultth
default February, 2011). In its re
defaults
defaultponse to the request, the BBC said:
default&#xa0;
default“defaultThe BBC did not undertake a significance assessment of making Radio 3 more accessible and welcoming. This is because it is not a new proposal, but ‘business as usual’: BBC Manag
defaultement has been seeking for some time to make its content more accessible and welcoming, and will continue to strive to do so. As such, no significance assessment was required.
default”default&#xa0;
defaultThis would suggest that the BBC Trust did not believe that a Public Value Test
default was appropriate because the change
defaults made to BBC Radio 3 took place 
defaultover a period of time, rather than at one single moment. However, the BBC Trust’s own protocols state that:
default&#xa0;
default“defaultA series of minor changes to a service licence may, cumulatively, require the 
defaultTrust to consider whether a further regulatory approvals process, such as a Public Value Test, is required.
default”default 
default              
default&#xa0;
defaultNot only should a Public Value Test have been undertaken, but also in failing to undertake a ‘significance assessment’ at all, the BBC Trust did
default not abide by the terms of the BBC Agreement with DCMS. 
default&#xa0;
defaultThere must be an overhaul of how BBC radio services are held accountable for their remit. As set out in the submission fr
defaultom
default our parent company, Global Radio, a new set of duties that take precedence
default over the BBC’s public purposes will ensure BBC services do not encroach on their private sector competitors. 
default&#xa0;
defaultBBC 
defaultRadio 3, along with all BBC radio services, must have a tighter remit in future for which management are accountable. This new remit must re
defaultassert 
defaultBBC 
defaultRadio
default 
default3’s duty to play specialist music throughout the schedule and ensure that the station does not duplicate content available on commercial services. 
