default&#xa0;
defaultThe latest round of 
defaultprogramming changes have been blamed on the need for the BBC to reduce costs. However, an analysis of the BBC’s annual report suggests that BBC Radio 3
default has an annual programme content 
defaultbudget of £38.3 million
default. 
defaultIt additionally spends £5.3 million on distribu
defaulttion, with a further £10.7 million spent on infrastructure and support. The BBC defines this latter figure as including: Property; HR; Policy and Strategy; Finance and Operations; and Marketing. It is important to note that these figures do not include the
default cost of newsgathering or of BBC Radio 3’s online digital services, which are accounted for separately. 
default&#xa0;
defaultThe BBC orchestras and performing groups receive total funding of £23.4 million per annum for content, with a further £5.8 million of infrastructure a
defaultnd support funding. 
default&#xa0;
defaultWhen added together, BBC Radio 3 and the BBC orchestras and performing groups spend £61.7 million on content, £5.3 million on distribution and £16.5 million on infrastructure and support – giving a grand total of £83.5 million of expe
defaultnditure in the 2012-13 financial year – an increase of 
default£2 million on the previous year. 
default&#xa0;
defaultThis is a huge amount of money. 
defaultBBC 
defaultRadio 3 cited the need to cut costs as the reason for the reduction in its commitment to specialist music programming from Septemb
defaulter 2013. However, given the scale of public money at 
defaultBBC 
defaultRadio 3’s disposal, there must surely be concern that the service is operating with a huge level of inefficiency for it not to be able to contain overall costs at a level that allowed these programme
defaults to continue. 
defaultFor this to be the case, we find it hard to believe that the stringent cost controls that would be in place in the commercial sector – out of commercial necessity - can possibly be being applied to a service that relies on a high level of gu
defaultaranteed public subsidy via the Licence Fee. 
default&#xa0;
defaultIt should also be noted that the live classical music market place already sees publicly funded orchestras in the geographic regions where the BBC funds additional orchestras. This is particularly the case in 
defaultLondon, Manchester and Glasgow
default, where it could be argued that the Licence Fee duplicates provision already funded via Arts Council England and the Scottish Government. 
default&#xa0;
defaultTHE CONCENTRATION OF POWERdefault&#xa0;defaultNowhere in the broadcasting or the arts world does
default so much power to spend such a large amount of public money rest in the hands of a single individual.
default&#xa0;
defaultThe Controller of Radio 3 is responsible for the UK’s biggest broadcaster of live classical music; the biggest commissioner of classical music; the UK’s 
defaultbiggest classical music festival (the BBC Proms); and responsibility for no fewer than five orchestras. 
default&#xa0;
defaultTo concentrate so much power in the hands of one individual
default 
defaulthas the potential to create
default an abuse of 
defaultthis market dominant position.
default 
defaultWe 
defaultremain concerned
default that this does not represent
default 
defaultthe best
default system for
default stewardship of a significa
defaultnt amount of licence fee money – and nor is it in the best interests o
defaultf creating a plural and diverse classical music ecosystem in the UK. 
default&#xa0;
defaultL
defaulticence 
defaultfunding in this area 
defaultshould be 
defaultopen to competition 
defaultto enable commercial operators to broadcast
default classical music concerts
default that are already funded or subsidised through Arts Council investment, perhaps through the creation of a ‘public service content publisher’ model, funded by a proporti
defaulton of the licence fee.
default 
default&#xa0;
defaultAdditionally, we are concerned that the creation in 2012 of The Space by the BBC and the Arts Council effectively creates a new publicly funded BBC service by the backdoor, without the usual checks and balances that are applied to the introduction of a new
default BBC channel. This 
defaultintroduces 
defaulta new level of 
defaultpublicly subsidised 
defaultcompetition to the classical music broadcasting marketplace that did not previously ex
defaultist. Given the move towards wider digital distribution of radio services, a brand new online channel supp
defaultor
defaultted through Licence Fee funding
default should not be regarded in isolation, but should be seen as being a part of the overall media marketplace. 
